body:
# Function Calling

Function calling enables OpenAI models to invoke structured tools during a conversation. You define tools with JSON Schema, the model decides when to call them, and your application executes the functions and returns results.

## Define Tools

Tools are defined as JSON Schema objects in the `tools` parameter:

```javascript
import OpenAI from "openai";

const client = new OpenAI(); // reads OPENAI_API_KEY from env

const tools = [
  {
    type: "function",
    function: {
      name: "get_weather",
      description: "Get the current weather for a location",
      parameters: {
        type: "object",
        properties: {
          location: {
            type: "string",
            description: "City and state (e.g. San Francisco, CA)",
          },
          unit: {
            type: "string",
            enum: ["celsius", "fahrenheit"],
            description: "Temperature unit",
          },
        },
        required: ["location"],
      },
    },
  },
  {
    type: "function",
    function: {
      name: "search_database",
      description: "Search a database for records matching a query",
      parameters: {
        type: "object",
        properties: {
          query: { type: "string", description: "Search query" },
          limit: { type: "integer", description: "Max results to return", default: 10 },
        },
        required: ["query"],
      },
    },
  },
];
```

## Handle Tool Calls

When the model wants to call a function, the response has `finish_reason: "tool_calls"` and a `tool_calls` array:

```javascript
const messages = [
  { role: "user", content: "What's the weather in San Francisco and New York?" },
];

const response = await client.chat.completions.create({
  model: "gpt-4o",
  messages,
  tools,
});

const choice = response.choices[0];

if (choice.finish_reason === "tool_calls") {
  // The model wants to call one or more functions
  const toolCalls = choice.message.tool_calls;

  // Add the assistant's message (with tool_calls) to the conversation
  messages.push(choice.message);

  // Execute each tool call and add results
  for (const toolCall of toolCalls) {
    const { name, arguments: args } = toolCall.function;
    const parsedArgs = JSON.parse(args);

    // Execute the function (your implementation)
    let result;
    if (name === "get_weather") {
      result = await getWeather(parsedArgs.location, parsedArgs.unit);
    } else if (name === "search_database") {
      result = await searchDatabase(parsedArgs.query, parsedArgs.limit);
    }

    // Add the tool result as a tool message
    messages.push({
      role: "tool",
      tool_call_id: toolCall.id,
      content: JSON.stringify(result),
    });
  }

  // Send the results back to the model for a final response
  const finalResponse = await client.chat.completions.create({
    model: "gpt-4o",
    messages,
    tools,
  });

  console.log(finalResponse.choices[0].message.content);
}
```

## Parallel Tool Calls

Models can request multiple tool calls in a single response. In the example above, asking about weather in two cities may produce two `get_weather` calls simultaneously:

```javascript
// toolCalls might contain:
// [{ function: { name: "get_weather", arguments: '{"location":"San Francisco, CA"}' } },
//  { function: { name: "get_weather", arguments: '{"location":"New York, NY"}' } }]
```

Process all calls, add all tool messages, then send the complete set back to the model. The model synthesizes all results into a coherent response.

To disable parallel tool calls, set `parallel_tool_calls: false`.

## Structured Output with Tools

Function calling is also a powerful mechanism for structured data extraction — even when you do not actually call an external function:

```javascript
const tools = [{
  type: "function",
  function: {
    name: "extract_contact",
    description: "Extract contact information from text",
    parameters: {
      type: "object",
      properties: {
        name: { type: "string" },
        email: { type: "string", format: "email" },
        phone: { type: "string" },
        company: { type: "string" },
      },
      required: ["name"],
    },
  },
}];

const response = await client.chat.completions.create({
  model: "gpt-4o",
  messages: [{ role: "user", content: "John Doe, john@example.com, works at Acme Corp" }],
  tools,
  tool_choice: { type: "function", function: { name: "extract_contact" } },
});

const extracted = JSON.parse(response.choices[0].message.tool_calls[0].function.arguments);
// { name: "John Doe", email: "john@example.com", company: "Acme Corp" }
```

Use `tool_choice` to force the model to call a specific function. This guarantees structured JSON output matching your schema. See also [[openai/chat#structured-output]] for the `response_format` approach.

## Tool Choice Options

| Value | Behavior |
|-------|----------|
| `"auto"` | Model decides whether to call tools (default) |
| `"none"` | Model will not call any tools |
| `"required"` | Model must call at least one tool |
| `{ type: "function", function: { name: "..." } }` | Model must call the specified function |

## In Assistants

Function calling works identically in the [[openai/assistants]] API. Define tools on the assistant, and when a run enters `requires_action` status, process the tool calls and submit outputs with `runs.submitToolOutputs()`. See [[openai/assistants#tools]] for details.
